    <text type="letter">
        <body> 
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc_es.00599.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place">Superindentent's Office.</name>
                    <name type="place">Asylum for the Insane,</name>
                    <name type="place">London, Ont.,</name>
                    <date when="1889-06-02">2 June 1889<ptr target="loc.07305_n1"/></date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>We have partly recovered here from the effects of the Ball which had rather a
                paralysing effect upon us. My daughter Clare<ptr target="loc.07233_n3"/> is still in
                bed but will be up in a day or two I trust. There is nothing in God's world more
                absurd than these balls &#38; parties at which one sits up all night pretending to
                have a good time and (without any pretence) has a very bad time for some days
                afterwards. I am impatient to hear about the W.W. dinner<ptr target="loc.03027_n4"/> I think I could have had a "good time" at that if I
                could have got there.<ptr target="loc.07305_n2"/> The weather here <choice>
                    <sic>keep</sic>
                    <corr>keeps</corr>
                </choice> singularly dark and cold. I am just at the end of poor O'Connor's<ptr
                    target="n2002"/> last book Mr. "Donnelly's Reviewers"<ptr target="loc.01172_n2"
                /> it is wonderfully clever.<ptr target="loc.07305_n4"/>&#8212;</p> 
            <closer>
                <signed>R M Bucke</signed>
            </closer>
